It goeth downe sweetely, but at the
last it biteth like a serpent, and poy
soneth like an adder. I will not re
hease all which I could alleadge out
of heathen writers, against surfetting
and drunkennesse. Solomon alone in
that one sentence conteyneth a great
deale of matter. Moreover, he that
heareth not Christ, whom is it likely
that he will give eare unto, in all the
worlde? Now Christ in the Gospell by
the parable of the rich glutton, doeth
mervaylous evidently set foorth the
wofull end of insatiable paunches. In
the same Gospell also he taketh occa
sion to touch the surfettings and dron
kennesse of our age, I meane the age
which is immediatly before ye Judge
ment day, where he saieth: As it hap
pened in the dayes of Noe and Lot,
they did eate and drinke even untill
the day that Noe entred into the arke
and that Lot departed from amonge
the Sodomits: and then inncontinent
ly the dluge came, and fire and brim
stone powred downe from heaven,
and destroyed them all. Againe he ad
deth: Take heede to your selves least
at anie time your heartes be overcome
with surfetting and drunkennesse, and
cares of this life, and so that day come
upon you at unawares. For as a snare
shall it come upon all them that dwell
uppon the face of the whole earth.
Watch ye therefore, at all times pray
ing, that ye may escape all these things
and stande before the sonne of man.
And I would to God ye all men would
not write this golden, heavenly, and
divine admonition of our Savior in
their halles, and dining parlours on
ly, but in their severall heartes also.

Moreover, he that heareth not Christ, whom is it likely that he will give eare unto, in all the worlde? Againe he ad deth: Take heede to your selves least at anie time your heartes be overcome with surfetting and drunkennesse, and cares of this life, and so that day come upon you at unawares. For as a snare shall it come upon all them that dwell uppon the face of the whole earth. Watch ye therefore, at all times pray ing, that ye may escape all these things and stande before the sonne of man. And I would to God ye all men would not write this golden, heavenly, and divine admonition of our Savior in their halles, and dining parlours on ly, but in their severall heartes also.
For since dronkennesse hath in these
our dayes so good intertainment with
all degrees, estates, kindes, and ages,
we doe daily feele the wofull miseries,
that God doth threaten to dronkards
in the 5. and 28. cap. of Esaies Prophe
cie. And it is to be feared greatly, that
the day of the Lord shall sobeinly light
uppon an innumerable fort of dron
kardes to their endlesse paine and ut
ter destruction. Let him heare there
fore, which hath eares to heare.
Neither can I heere refraine, but
needes must recite unto you (dearely
beloved) that which S. Martine ye bi
shop, not of Tours in Fraunce, but of
Dumia in Germanie, who flourished
in ye daies of Justinian the Emperour,
did write to Miro kinge of Gallicia
touching ye ordering and leading a co
tinent life. If (saith he) thou dost love
continencie, cut off superfluitie, and
keepe under thine appetite. Consider
with thy selfe howe much nature re
quireth, and not howe must lust desi
reth. Bridle thy cocupiscnece, and cast
off the alluring baytes that serve to
drawe on hidden pleasures. Eate with
out undigested surfetting, and drinke
without dronkennesse. Neither glut
thy selfe with present delicates, nor
long after deintrelles hard to be come
bye. Let thy dyet bee of cates good
cheape, and sit not downe for pleasure
but for meate. Let hunger, not sauces
provoke thee to eate. Pay but little
for pastimes to delight thee, because
thy onely care should be to leave such
pleasures, that thereby thou in fashio
ning thy selfe to the example of God,
mayest, as much as thou canst, make
haste to reduce thy selfe from the bo
die to the spirite. If thou lovest con
tinencie, then choose not a pleasaunt,
but a wholesome dwelling place, and
make not the Lorde to be knowen by
